The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 Mumbai, April 23: Sebi has asked brokers not to refuse services to investors in case they fail to furnish power of attorney in favour of them. Power of attorney is a legal arrangement that allows brokers to access bank and demat accounts of their clients. The guidelines said brokers would be prohibited from using client accounts for off-market trade.                            
	 New Delhi, April 23: The government has cleared 18 FDI proposals worth Rs 344.33 crore. The highest FDI of Rs 308.20 crore is likely to come from Abbott Capital India, which plans to acquire a 20 per cent stake in drug maker Solvays Indian business.                            
	 New Delhi, April 23: French drug maker Sanofi Aventis SA said the New Jersey district court had ordered Sun Pharma to stop selling its generic version of Eloxatin chemotherapy, used in treating colon cancer.                            
	 New Delhi, April 23: The RBI has asked all banks to put in place additional security measures for credit card transactions based on interactive voice response (IVR) by January 1, 2011. IVR allows people to access their bank or credit card information through automated responses over the phone, instead of having to speak to staff.                            
	 Athens, April 23: Greece went cap in hand to the EU and IMF today, appealing for up to 45 billion euros of urgent aid at low rates this year in a grim turn for the eurozone now threatened by Greek contagion.                             
	 New York, April 23: Goldman Sachs director Rajat Gupta had tipped off Raj Rajaratnam, an accused in the insider trading scam, about a deal between Buffett-led Berkshire Hathaway and the Wall Street giant, before the public announcement, the Wall Street Journal said today.                            
	 Mumbai, April 23: Pantaloon Retail will demerge three of its businesses, including food, into two of its subsidiaries.                                                                                                                          
